The Working Moms

Introduction

The 2013 American Community Survey run by the US Census Bureau provides a rich dataset with detailed information of approximately 3.5 million households regarding to topics such as ancestry, education, employment, and residency. Being a working mom myself, Im particularly interested in a descriptive analysis of the employment status of the American moms with dependent children younger than 18 years old.

Dataset

The variables including information of region, age, marital status, presence of kids, employment status, education, and wage were read into R and saved as pus.Rdata. Male at any age and female younger than 16 years old were removed from the dataset by omitting the instances with NA in the PAOC (presence of own children) variable.

The catagorical variables were labled according to ACS data dictionary. The am dataset contained three groups of moms including moms with little kids (children under 6), moms with big kids (children 6 to 17), and moms with little kids and old kids (children under 6 and 6 to 17) according to the information of presence of children (PAOC).

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(gridExtra)
library(maps)
load("pus.Rdata")

pus$MAR <- factor(pus$MAR)
levels(pus$MAR) <- c("Married", "Widowed", "Divorced", "Separated", "Never married")

pus$ESR <- factor(pus$ESR)
levels(pus$ESR) <- c("Employed", "Employed, not at work", "Unemployed", "Employed", "Employed, not at work", "Not in labor force")
pus$ESRG <- ifelse(pus$ESR == "Employed", 1, 0)

pus$COW <- factor(pus$COW)
levels(pus$COW) <- c("Private profit", "Private non-profit", "Local government", "State government", "Federal government", "Self-employed", "Self-employed", "Working without pay", "Unemployed")

pus$PAOC <- factor(pus$PAOC)
levels(pus$PAOC) <- c("Children under 6", "Children 6 to 17", "Children under 6 and 6 to 17", "No children")
pus$PAOCG <- ifelse(pus$PAOC == "No children", 0, 1)

pus$SCHL <- ifelse(pus$SCHL <= 16, 16, pus$SCHL)
pus$SCHL <- ifelse(pus$SCHL >= 17 & pus$SCHL <= 19, 19, pus$SCHL)
pus$SCHL <- factor(pus$SCHL)
levels(pus$SCHL) <- c("High school or lower", "Some college", "Associate's degree", "Bachelor's degree", "Master's degree", "Professional degree", "Doctorate degree")

am <- subset(pus, PAOCG == 1)

Observation

Being a mom with dependent children is a transient stage in a womens life. Roughly a quarter of the women older than 16 were with dependent children, and only 5.8% of them were with little kids younger than 6 years old. The age distribution of the moms was bell-shaped with a median value of 38 and interquantile range of 13. The median ages of moms with little kids, moms with big kids, and moms with both were 30, 43, and 34 respectively.

Marital Status

data <- as.data.frame(prop.table(table(am$AGEP, am$MAR)))
data$margin <- prop.table(table(am$AGEP))
data$height <- data$Freq/data$margin
data$center <- c(0, cumsum(data$margin)[1:length(levels(factor(am$AGEP))) -1]) + data$margin/2
ggplot(data, aes(center, height)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(width = margin, fill = Var2), col = "gray", alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Frequency", title = "Marital Status of the Moms") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.1), labels=c("16", "27", "31", "33", "36", "38", "41", "43", "46", "50", "93"))

Observation

Roughly three quarters of the moms with dependent children were married, and the percentage of being married remained relatively constant among the moms in their 30s or 40s. The single moms at younger age were more likely to be never married, while the single moms at older age were more likely to be divorced or separated.

Approximately one third of the moms with dependent children possessed a Bachelors degree or higher. The moms in their 30s or 40s showed higher education level compared to the moms at their young age, eg., 17% of the moms at age 45 had a Masters degree or higher in comparison to 2% of the moms at age 25.

The Working Moms

Employment Status

data <- as.data.frame(prop.table(table(am$AGEP, am$ESR)))
data$margin <- prop.table(table(am$AGEP))
data$height <- data$Freq/data$margin
data$center <- c(0, cumsum(data$margin)[1:length(levels(factor(am$AGEP))) -1]) + data$margin/2
ggplot(data, aes(center, height)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(width = margin, fill = Var2), col = "gray", alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Frequency", title = "Employment Status of the Moms") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.1), labels=c("16", "27", "31", "33", "36", "38", "41", "43", "46", "50", "93"))

Observation

While its largely a personal choice to be a working mom or not, there might be objective factors that influence the moms decision. A rough look at the plot of employmennt status showed that overall 65% of the moms were employed and active at work. The proportion of employment steadily increased with the moms age among moms younger than 50 years old, suggesting that more moms continued their career track when their kids grew older. Meanwhile, the proportion of being unemployed dropped accordingly with the moms age.

Marital Status vs Employment Status

chisq.test(table(am$MAR, am$ESR))
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(am$MAR, am$ESR)
## X-squared = 8701.7, df = 12, p-value < 2.2e-16
data <- as.data.frame(prop.table(table(am$MAR, am$ESR), margin = 1))
ggplot(data, aes(x = Var1, y = Freq, group = Var2)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(colour = Var2, fill = Var2), alpha = 0.3) + 
  labs(x = "Marital Status", y = "Frequency", title = "Marital Status vs Employment Status")

Observation

The Chi square test suggested a highly significant association between marital status and employment status among the moms with dependent children. The highest percentage of being employed were seen in the group of divorced moms (77%), followed with the group of separated moms (68%), who were more likely to be facing double pressure of taking care of children and being financially independent.

Education vs Employment Status

chisq.test(table(am$SCHL, am$ESR))
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(am$SCHL, am$ESR)
## X-squared = 13578, df = 18, p-value < 2.2e-16
data <- as.data.frame(prop.table(table(am$SCHL, am$ESR), margin = 1))
ggplot(data, aes(x = Var1, y = Freq, group = Var2)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(colour = Var2, fill = Var2), alpha = 0.3) + 
  labs(x = "Education", y = "Frequency", title = "Education vs Employment Status") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1))

Observation

The Chi square test also revealed a significant association between education and employment status among the moms. Approximately 80% of the moms with advanced degrees (Masters degree or higher) were employed and active at work, while the percentage of employment was only about 53% among the moms with high school education or lower.

Wages of the Working Mom

wm <- subset(am, ESR == "Employed" & WAGP > 1000)
wm$AGEG <- cut(wm$AGEP, breaks = quantile(wm$AGEP))
ggplot(na.omit(wm), aes(x = AGEG, y = log10(WAGP))) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = AGEG), alpha = 0.5) + 
  labs(x = "Age Group", y = "Wage on Log10 Scale", title = "Wages vs Age Groups")

Observation

The instances of working moms were divided into four age groups (16 to 33, 34 to 39, 40 to 45, and 46 to 93) according to their age quantiles. When the wages were plotted according to age groups, a significant increment was shown between the first and the second groups. The wages of working moms in the second, third and fourth age groups remained relatively on the same level.

ggplot(na.omit(wm), aes(x = COW, y = log10(WAGP))) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = COW), alpha = 0.5) + 
  labs(x = "Field of Work", y = "Wageon Log10 Scale", title = "Wages vs Field of Work") +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, aes(colour = AGEG), geom="point", size = 5) +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, aes(group=AGEG, colour = AGEG), geom="line") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1)) + 
  guides(fill = FALSE)

ggplot(na.omit(wm), aes(x = MAR, y = log10(WAGP))) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = MAR), alpha = 0.5) + 
  labs(x = "Marital Status", y = "Wageon Log10 Scale", title = "Wages vs Marital Status") +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, aes(colour = AGEG), geom="point", size = 5) +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, aes(group=AGEG, colour = AGEG), geom="line") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1)) + 
  guides(fill = FALSE)

ggplot(na.omit(wm), aes(x = SCHL, y = log10(WAGP))) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = SCHL), alpha = 0.5) + 
  labs(x = "Education", y = "Wageon Log10 Scale", title = "Wages vs Education") +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, aes(colour = AGEG), geom="point", size = 5) +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, aes(group=AGEG, colour = AGEG), geom="line") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1)) + 
  guides(fill = FALSE)

Observation

The wages of working moms were plotted according to factors of field of work, marital status and education respectively, with the mean wage of each age groups labeled as points of various colors. In addition to the higher employment rate, moms with advanced degrees were more likely to have higer wages compared to moms with lower education levels. Besides, moms working for federal government showed the highest mean wages among all categories of field of work. Still, the group of moms ages 16 to 33 represented the lowest mean wages among the four age groups.

Observation

There was regional differences regarding to the employment rate of moms as well as wages of working moms with dependent children. The midwest States (South Dakota, Iowa, Minnesota, Wisconsin, and Nebraska) and the southeast States (Arizona, New Mexico, California, and Utah) represented the extreme cases of highest and lowest rates of moms being employed. The highest wages of working moms were shown in the northeast States (District of Columbia, Maryland, Massachusetts, Connecticut, and New Jersey).

Summary

Here is a brief summary about working moms with dependent children in the United States from a glance at the dataset of the 2013 American Community Survey: Two out of three moms with dependent children were working moms, and the likelyhood of being a working mom slightly increased with the moms age. Being a working mom or not was significantly associated with the moms marital status and education level; divorced moms and moms with advanced degrees had the highest likelyhood to be working moms. Moms in the midwest region had the highest likelyhood of being a working mom, while moms in the sourtheast region has the lowest likelyhood. The wages of working moms were associated with the moms age, marital status, field of work, education, as well as residency.
